Expectations and acceptance. 🙏💭

One will make you over think and may lead to emotional draining and frustration. The other will help you settle in, look forward to a new day and build a stronger will.

If you have spent a fair amount of time practicing scorpion (any skill for that matter), patiently waited to close in those 2-3 inches while working regularly on those back bending drills; you’d know my reference with the above two words very well.

This one required a lot of patience and time. I can still do better and get in another inch but I’ll take this moment to appreciate this journey. You could checkout my previous scorpion post and see the difference in the range. 

Thank you for everything @manoj_handstand You’re special. 🙏🧘‍♂️🐉

latestIgtvVideos.title: How much are you willing to put in ?
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
.
Our bodies are similar to plants in various ways including growth and progress. It’s the same when working on a skill or a movement. Sometimes you grows fast and sometimes at a comfortable pace.⁣
⁣
What makes the difference is that extra mile and consistency. This video basically shows the journey of @karan_k1998 who from not being able to lift the leg off the floor, now has an L-sit on his fingers. This isn’t the final position as the goal is to be able to lift it off the floor. We might close it in a week, max. But honestly, it doesn’t seem that important anymore after looking at this reel and the journey. Consistency and being honest with your practice could really get you places. He’s back at his University in Boston and continuing online training to now slowly move towards V-sit.⁣
⁣
I don’t want to make this too philosophical. Not that I am good at it. This isn’t about me but about @karan_k1998 and how he had his first L’s in 4 weeks but we decided to get it off the floor. Most of the people can perform an L-sit off the parallettes. But as you keep going lower, it keeps getting tougher.⁣
⁣
Have a good weekend guys.⁣
⁣
Thanks. 🙏🐉⁣
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

latestIgtvVideos.title: DO YOU LOSE YOUR OLD SKILLS ?
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
⁣⁣
.
.
Looking at my practice from today, this was my third set and probably the smoothest one. In my opinion it might take a couple of attempts maybe at the beginning to be at the best position but yes it stays. You achieve a skill as and when your muscle groups, brain and joints matures towards it. A skill is achieved and owned over a period of time and during that phase the body gets conditioned and prepared at different positions, ranges and patterns. There’s a difference between owning a skill and being able to just perform a skill. Owning a skill takes longer and more understanding.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Also the body doesn’t lose a movement or skill easily for one simple reason “infinite repetitions” being drilled into your nervous system. All the sessions during which the body was forced to touch those ranges or goals, are well registered by the system. So the body keeps them.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Also need to place the sliders better next time. Got stuck with my right side but left was able to take the load.⁣
⁣
Thanks.🙏🐉⁣⁣
.
.
.
.
.

latestIgtvVideos.caption:
In my experience the most important factor involved while training strength and mobility is determination and mental endurance. 
Ultimately, your ability to attach your will to something and perseverance is what strength actually is. It's all a mental game because if the mind and spirit aren't cooperating it will feel lackluster. 🐉🙏 Sharing my work from today inspired by some amazing Teachers @devinpkelley @chrisfoxyoga @naprapatjonas 🙏
